            <p class="text-justify">
                Manipuri dance, sometimes also referred to as the Manipuri Raas Leela (Meitei: Jagoi Raas/Raas Jagoi[1][2][3]), is a jagoi and is one of the major Indian classical dance forms, originating from the state of Manipur. This dance form is considered to be the highest spiritual expression of the worship of Hindu deity Krishna. It is a portrayal of the dance of divine love of Krishna with goddess Radha and the cowherd damsels of Vrindavan, famously known as the Raas Leela. It is one of the eight major Indian classical dance forms and has its roots in the northeastern state of Manipur in India. The Manipuri classical dance is also referred to as the Manipuri Raas Leela. </p>
